  "doc_id": "56579",
  "text": "We sought to identify promoters induced by exposure to conditions inside the mouse peritoneum but repressed by growth in rich medium. A DFI enrichment strategy was used, as described above. From a promoter trap library of ca. 16,000 clones, 11 promoters were found after screening and sequencing steps, to be unique ( Table 1 ). The ratio of in vivo to in vitro fluorescence ranged from 2.9 to 24. All 11 clones matched sequence in CFT073, but three matched putative promoter regions for ORFs of uncertain function. The eight remaining were linked to genes encoding a diverse range of proteins involved in siderophore synthesis, metabolism, regulation, and adherence. Iron acquisition. Of the 11 promoters, 3 appear to be linked to iron acquisition genes. The siderophore enterobactin is represented on clone 1217, which contains on its insert the promoter of entC, encoding the first enzyme in enterobactin synthesis [CITATION_1] . Another clone, 1031, contains the start of the aerobactin synthesis operon, iucABCD, while a third clone, 723, contains the promoter for irp2, the first gene of the operon for yersiniabactin synthesis [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] .",
